title: Projected resident population, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians, identification change series, sex and age groups by states and territories and Australia, 2021 to 2031
description: Contains estimates and projections of the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population based on the 2021 Census of Population and Housing, by sex and five-year age groups, for the period 2006 to 2031. Population projections illustrate how the Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population would change in the future as a result of certain assumptions. This dataset presents 9 scenarios, comprising combinations of different rates of fertility, paternity, mortality, interstate migration and overseas migration. Unit of measure: Projected Persons. Geographic coverage: Australia/State. Catalogue number: 3238.0

title: Projected resident population, Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians, identification change series, sex and age groups by Remoteness Areas, 2021 to 2031
description: Contains estimates and projections (based on assumptions on past and future fertility, mortality and migration) of the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population based on the 2021 Census of Population and Housing for Indigenous Regions and Remoteness Areas by sex and five-year age groups, for the period 2017 to 2031. Population projections illustrate how the Australian Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population would change in the future as a result of certain assumptions. This dataset presents 9 scenarios, comprising combinations of different rates of fertility, paternity, mortality, interstate migration and overseas migration. Unit of measure: Projected Persons. Geographic coverage: Remoteness Areas. Catalogue number: 3238.0

title: Australian Census Longitudinal Dataset (ACLD): Labour force status, 2006-2011

title: Census 2021, G02 Selected medians and averages, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Selected medians and averages data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census.
Median age of persons excludes overseas visitors.
Median total personal income is applicable to persons aged 15 years and over.
Median total family income is applicable to families in family households. It excludes families where at least one member aged 15 years and over did not state an income and families where at 
least one member aged 15 years and over was temporarily absent on Census Night. 
Median total household income is applicable to occupied private dwellings. It excludes households where at least one member aged 15 years and over did not state an income and 
households where at least one member aged 15 years and over was temporarily absent on Census Night. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households. 
Median mortgage repayment is applicable to occupied private dwellings being purchased and includes dwellings being purchased under a shared equity scheme. It excludes 'Visitors only' 
and 'Other non-classifiable' households. 
Median rent is applicable to occupied private dwellings being rented. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households. 
For 2021, median rent calculations exclude dwellings being 'Occupied rent-free' and will not be comparable to 2016 Census data.
Average number of persons per bedroom is applicable to occupied private dwellings. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households. 
Average household size is applicable to number of persons usually resident in occupied private dwellings. It includes partners, children, and co-tenants (in group households) who were
temporarily absent on Census Night. A maximum of three temporary absentees can be counted in each household. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households.

title: Census 2021, G03 Place of usual residence by place of enumeration on Census Night by age, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Place of usual residence by place of enumeration on Census Night by age data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of persons (excludes overseas visitors).
This table is based on place of enumeration.
This table counts persons where they were staying on Census Night. It shows the number of persons who were at home on Census Night and the number of persons who were visiting away from their usual residence. 
For persons visiting away from their usual residence, it shows which SA2 they were visiting from, i.e. either interstate, intrastate or from within the same SA2 area.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

title: Census 2021, G06 Social marital status by age by sex, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Social marital status by age by sex data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of persons aged 15 years and over.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
Excludes persons in 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households, 'Non-private dwellings', and 'Migratory, off-shore and shipping' SA1s. Excludes persons who were temporarily absent on Census Night.
In December 2017, amendments to the Marriage Act 1961 came into effect enabling marriage equality for all couples. For 2021, registered marriages include all couples.
'Married in a de facto marriage' means two people live together as partners who are not in a registered marriage. It includes people who report de facto, partner, common law husband/wife/spouse, lover, girlfriend or boyfriend.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

Ancestry by country of birth of parents data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of responses and persons.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
This list of ancestries consists of the most common 30 Ancestry responses reported in the 2016 Census. 
This table is a multi-response table and therefore the total responses count will not equal the total persons count.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

title: Census 2021, G18 Core activity need for assistance by age by sex, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Core activity need for assistance by age by sex data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of persons.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
Measures the number of people with a profound or severe core activity limitation. People with a profound or severe core activity limitation are those needing assistance in their day to day lives in one or more of the three core activity areas of self-care, mobility and communication because of a long-term health condition (lasting six months or more), a disability (lasting six months or more), or old age.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

title: Census 2021, G19 Type of long-term health condition by age by sex, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Type of long-term health condition by age by sex data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of responses and persons.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
Measures the number of people who reported that they have been told by a doctor or nurse that they have any of these long-term health conditions. Includes health conditions that have lasted or are expected to last six months or more, may occur from time to time, are controlled by medication or are in remission. 
Respondents had the option to record multiple long-term health conditions therefore the sum of total responses count will not equal the total person count.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

title: Census 2021, G20 Count of selected long-term health conditions by age by sex, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Count of selected long-term health conditions by age by sex data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of persons.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
Measures the number of people who reported that they have been told by a doctor or nurse that they have one or more of the following selected long-term health conditions: arthritis, asthma, cancer (including remission), dementia (including Alzheimer's), diabetes (excluding gestational diabetes), heart disease (including heart attack or angina), kidney disease, lung condition (including COPD or emphysema), mental health condition (including depression or anxiety) and stroke. title: Census 2021, G21 Type of long-term health condition by selected person characteristics, Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries)
description:
Type of long-term health condition by selected person characteristics data for Commonwealth Electoral Divisions (CED 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of responses and persons.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
Measures the number of people who reported that they have been told by a doctor or nurse that they have any of these long-term health conditions. Includes health conditions that have lasted or are expected to last six months or more, may occur from time to time, are controlled by medication or are in remission.
Respondents had the option to record multiple long-term health conditions therefore the sum of total responses count will not equal the total person count.
Total personal income and Australia Defence Force service is applicable to persons aged 15 years and over.
Core activity need for assistance is a person's need for help or assistance in one or more of the three core activity areas of self-care, mobility and communication, because of a disability, long-term health condition (lasting six months or more) or old age.
Australian Defence Force service includes Royal Australian Navy, Australian Army, Royal Australian Air Force, Second Australian Imperial Force, National Service and NORFORCE. Excludes service for non-Australian Defence forces. Includes service in the Regular Service and/or Reserves Service.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

title: Census 2021, T02 Selected medians and averages, Time Series, Local Government Area 2021 (LGA 2021 boundaries)
description:
Selected medians and averages time series data for Local Government Area 2021 (LGA 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census.
Median age of persons excludes overseas visitors. 
Median total personal income is applicable to persons aged 15 years and over.
Median total family income is applicable to families in family households. It excludes families where at least one family member aged 15 years and over did not state an income, and
families where at least one member aged 15 years and over was temporarily absent on Census Night. 
Median total household income is applicable to occupied private dwellings. It excludes households where at least one member aged 15 years and over did not state an income and
households where at least one member aged 15 years and over was temporarily absent on Census Night. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households.
Median mortgage repayment is applicable to occupied private dwellings being purchased and includes dwellings being purchased under a shared equity scheme. It excludes
Visitors only' 'and 'Other non-classifiable' households. 
Median rent is applicable to occupied private dwellings being rented. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households. 
Median rent excludes dwellings being 'Occupied rent-free'.
Average number of persons per bedroom is applicable to occupied private dwellings. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households.
Average household size is applicable to number of persons usually resident in occupied private dwellings. Includes partners, children, and co-tenants (in group households) who
were temporarily absent on Census Night. A maximum of three temporary absentees can be counted in each household. It excludes 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' 
households.

title: Census 2021, T05 Social marital status by age by sex, Time Series, Local Government Area 2021 (LGA 2021 boundaries)
description:
Social marital status by age by sex time series data for Local Government Area 2021 (LGA 2021 boundaries), 2021 Census, Count of persons aged 15 years and over.
This table is based on place of usual residence.
Excludes persons in 'Visitors only' and 'Other non-classifiable' households, 'Non-private dwellings', and 'Migratory, off-shore and shipping' SA1s. Excludes persons who were temporarily absent on Census Night.

In December 2017, amendments to the Marriage Act 1961 came into effect enabling marriage equality for all couples. For 2021, registered marriages include all couples.

'Married in a de facto marriage' means two people live together as partners who are not in a registered marriage. It includes people who report de facto, partner, common law husband/wife/spouse, lover, girlfriend or boyfriend.
Please note that there are small random adjustments made to all cell values to protect the confidentiality of data. These adjustments may cause the sum of rows or columns to differ by small amounts from table totals.

title: Provisional Mortality Statistics: Number of deaths by Sex, Age and State of registration, by month of occurrence
description: Provisional Monthly Mortality Statistics: Contains preliminary death counts by month of occurrence for Australia. Death counts include both doctor certified and coroner certified deaths. This series was introduced in June 2020 in response to the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia. This data provides an early indication of the pattern of mortality. There are many factors that influences counts of deaths on a monthly basis, including time required for coronial investigations and timeliness of death registrations. These considerations should be taken into account when interpreting data.  Monthly occurrence data is available from 2015 onwards. Death counts are not comparable to those reported in Deaths, Australia or Causes of Death, Australia.

title: Provisional Mortality Statistics by Selected causes of death, by month of occurrence
description: Provisional Monthly Mortality Statistics: Contains preliminary death counts by month of occurrence for Australia. Death counts contain doctor certified deaths only. This series was introduced in June 2020 in response to the COVID-19 pandemic in Australia. This data provides an early indication of the pattern of mortality. There are many factors that influences counts of deaths on a monthly basis, including time required for coronial investigations and timeliness of death registrations. These considerations should be taken into account when interpreting data.  Monthly occurrence data is available from 2015 onwards. Death counts are not comparable to those reported in Deaths, Australia or Causes of Death, Australia.

title: Provisional Mortality Statistics by Selected causes of death, by week of occurrence
description: Provisional Weekly Mortality Statistics: Contains preliminary death counts by week of occurrence for Australia. Death counts contain doctor certified deaths only. There are many factors that influences counts of deaths on a weekly basis, including time required for coronial investigations and timeliness of death registrations. These considerations should be taken into account when interpreting data.  Weekly occurrence data is available from 2015 onwards. Death counts are not comparable to those reported in Deaths, Australia or Causes of Death, Australia.

title: Provisional Mortality Statistics: Number of deaths by Sex, Age and State of registration, by week of occurrence
description: Provisional Weekly Mortality Statistics: Contains preliminary death counts by week of occurrence for Australia. Death counts include both doctor certified and coroner certified deaths. title: SEIFA 2011 by Postal Area Code (POA)
description: Consists of four indexes based on Census data: Index of Relative Socio-economic Disadvantage (IRSD); Index of Relative Socio-economic Advantage and Disadvantage (IRSAD); Index of Education and Occupation (IEO) and Index of Economic Resources (IER). Each index is a summary of Census variables and focuses on a different aspect of socio-economic advantage and disadvantage. Postal Areas are an ABS approximation of postcodes (post codes) created to enable the release of ABS data on areas that, as closely as possible, approximate postcodes. This enables the comparison of ABS data with other data collected using postcodes as the geographic reference. Unit of measure: Index. Geographic coverage: ASGS2011 Postal Code Area (POA). Catalogue number: 2033.0.55.001

title: SEIFA 2011 by Statistical Area 1 (SA1)
description: Consists of four indexes based on Census data: Index of Relative Socio-economic Disadvantage (IRSD); Index of Relative Socio-economic Advantage and Disadvantage (IRSAD); Index of Education and Occupation (IEO) and Index of Economic Resources (IER). Each index is a summary of Census variables and focuses on a different aspect of socio-economic advantage and disadvantage. Unit of measure: Index. Geographic coverage: ASGS 2011 Australia/State/SA1. Catalogue number: 2033.0.55.001

title: SEIFA 2011 by State Suburb Code (SSC)
description: Socio-Economic Indexes for Areas (SEIFA) ranks areas in Australia according to relative socio-economic advantage and disadvantage. It consists of four indexes based on Census data: Index of Relative Socio-economic Disadvantage (IRSD); Index of Relative Socio-economic Advantage and Disadvantage (IRSAD); Index of Education and Occupation (IEO) and Index of Economic Resources (IER). Each index is a summary of a different subset of Census variables and focuses on a different aspect of socio-economic advantage and disadvantage. Unit of measure: Index. Geographic coverage: ASS 2011 State Suburb Code (SSC). Catalogue number: 2033.0.55.001

title: Perturbed Student Enrolments Pivot Table 2023 - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Allows for customised higher education student enrolment tables, with time series data from 2018.To avoid the risk of disseminating identifiable data, a disclosure control technique called input perturbation has been applied to the data within the Pivot Table, whereby small random adjustments are made to cell counts. For more details see the 'Explanatory Notes' within the pivot table.  Aggregates within the Pivot Tables may not match other tables. Where unperturbed figures are required, users should consult the Higher Education Statistics published on the department’s website.

title: Perturbed Student Load Pivot Table 2023 - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Allows for customised higher education student enrolment tables, with time series data from 2018.To avoid the risk of disseminating identifiable data, a disclosure control technique called input perturbation has been applied to the data within the Pivot Table, whereby small random adjustments are made to cell counts. title: 2023 Student summary tables - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education student enrolment and EFTSL (Equivalent Full-time Student Load) summary tables for the 2023 full year.

title: 2023 Student summary time series - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education student enrolment summary time series statistics full year, 2012-2023

title: 2023 Section 1 - Commencing students - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education commencing student enrolment tables for the 2023 full year. Commencing students are persons who have enrolled for the first time in a particular course at a particular higher education institution during the reference period.

title: 2023 Section 2 - All students - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education all student enrolment tables for the 2023 full year. All students include commencing and continuing students.

title: 2023 Section 3 - Commencing student load - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education commencing student EFTSL (Equivalent Full-time Student Load) tables for the 2023 full year. Commencing students are persons who have enrolled for the first time in a particular course at a particular higher education institution during the reference period.

title: 2023 Section 4 - All student load - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education all student EFTSL (Equivalent Full-time Student Load) tables for the 2023 full year. All students include commencing and continuing students.

title: 2023 Section 5 - Liability status - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education liability status categories tables for the 2023 full year. These tables provide information on a student’s status for a unit of study (Commonwealth Supported place, scholarship holder and fee-paying).

title: 2023 Section 6 - First Nations students - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education First Nations student tables for the 2023 full year. First Nations students are those who self-identify as being of Australian Aboriginal and/or Torres Strait Islander descent.

title: 2023 Section 7 - Overseas students - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education overseas student tables for the 2023 full year. Overseas students includes students who have temporary entry visas, or are diplomats or a dependent of a diplomat (except New Zealand) and reside in Australia during the unit of study, and non-domestic students residing outside Australia during the unit of study.

title: 2023 Section 8 - Special courses - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education special courses tables for the 2023 full year. Students undertaking special courses include courses that: provide for initial registration as nurses; provide for initial teacher training; lead to provisional registration as a medical practitioner; lead to provisional registration as a veterinary practitioner; lead to provisional registration as a dental practitioner; lead to provisional registration as a clinical psychologist practitioner; or relate to a course of study in aviation as listed in the FEE-HELP Guidelines 2017.

title: 2023 Section 9 - Domestic students ethnicity related data - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education ethnicity related tables for the 2023 full year. These tables provide information on country of birth and language spoken at home.

title: 2023 Section 10 - Open Universities Australia - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education student enrolment and EFTSL (Equivalent Full-time Student Load) tables for the 2023 full year offered through Open Universities Australia (OUA). Units of study from a higher education course offered by OUA can be counted as credit towards a higher education institution degree.

title: 2023 Section 11 - Equity groups - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education equity groups tables for the 2023 full year. Equity groups include students that: are from non-English speaking backgrounds (NESB); have a disability; are women in non-traditional areas; identify as First Nations; are from low SES (socioeconomic status) locations; and are from regional and remote locations.

title: 2023 Section 12 - Academic organisational units - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education academic organisational unit tables for the 2023 full year. An academic organisational unit group provides a means for standardising academic organisational units across institutions. Academic organisational units are assigned to an academic organisational unit group on the basis of disciplines for which each academic organisational unit has a teaching and/or research responsibility.

title: 2023 Section 13 - Private Universities (Table C) and Non-University Higher Education Institutions - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Private University (Table C) and Non-University Higher Education Institution tables for the 2023 full year. Tables include data on student enrolments, student EFTSL (Equivalent Full-time Student Load), success rates and completions.

title: 2023 Section 14 - Award course completions - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education award course completion tables for the 2023 full year. Award course completions are conferred after the successful completion of all the academic requirements of a course which includes any required attendance, assignments, examinations, assessments, dissertations, practical experience and work experience in industry.

title: 2023 Section 15 - Attrition, success and retention - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education attrition, success and retention rate tables for the 2023 full year.

title: 2023 Section 16 - Equity Performance Data - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Higher education equity performance tables for 2023 full year.

title: 2023 Section 17 - Completion Rates - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: Completion rates reports present the results of tracking commencing higher education student outcomes over time. That is, after nominated periods, how many commencing students have completed their studies, how many are still studying, and how many have not completed an award course. Cohort analysis publications also present outcomes of students by selected characteristics.

title: Building a better and fairer education system - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Australian Government is reforming the entire education system to build a better and fairer Australia. Reforms include:cutting the cost of early education and care for around one million familiesfixing the funding of our public schools and tying that funding to real reform, andcutting student debt by a further 20%.

title: 2025–26 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Department of Education works to ensure Australians can experience the wellbeing and economic benefits that quality education provides.

title: 2024–25 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Budget 2024-25 invests in all areas of education and prioritises equity and opportunity as the Government continues to build a better and fairer education system for all Australians.

title: 2024–25 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Budget 2024-25 invests in all areas of education and prioritises equity and opportunity as the Government continues to build a better and fairer education system for all Australians.

title: 2023–24 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Budget 2023–24 invests in Australia’s education workforce, and works to build a better and fairer education system for the future. The Budget provides targeted funding across early education, schools and higher education and invests in the skills-needs of early childhood educators to maximise the benefits for families from Cheaper Child Care.

title: 2023–24 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Budget 2023–24 invests in Australia’s education workforce, and works to build a better and fairer education system for the future. The Budget provides targeted funding across early education, schools and higher education and invests in the skills-needs of early childhood educators to maximise the benefits for families from Cheaper Child Care.

title: 2022–23 October Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Budget October 2022–23 invests in better education for all Australians, in early education and care, schools and universities. The Budget provides record funding for early childhood education and care, through the Government’s $4.5* billion Plan for Cheaper Child Care. It also invests in measures that open the door of opportunity wider for Australians from all backgrounds.

title: 2022–23 October Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Budget October 2022–23 invests in better education for all Australians, in early education and care, schools and universities. The Budget provides record funding for early childhood education and care, through the Government’s $4.5* billion Plan for Cheaper Child Care. It also invests in measures that open the door of opportunity wider for Australians from all backgrounds.

title: 2022-23 March Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The 2022-23 Budget invests in measures that support Australian families, strengthens student educational outcomes, and will help secure Australia’s ongoing economic recovery through skills and employment.

title: 2021-22 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The 2021-22 Budget invests in measures that support Australian families, strengthens student educational outcomes, and will help secure Australia’s ongoing economic recovery through skills and employment.

title: 2021-22 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The 2021-22 Budget invests in measures that support Australian families, strengthens student educational outcomes, and will help secure Australia’s ongoing economic recovery through skills and employment.

title: 2020-21 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The 2020-21 Budget is committing record funding to rebuilding our economy and securing Australia’s future. Investing in apprenticeships, creating jobs and boosting the skills of Australians to help them get back into work is at the heart of the Government’s Economic Recovery Plan for Australia, along with guaranteeing the essential services Australians rely on. These services include supporting Australia’s education system through the continued provision of quality early childhood education, and funding certainty for schools and universities, while delivering more VET and higher education places, short courses and investing in research. The employment services system will continue to be reformed to be able to better meet the needs of Australians looking for work.

title: 2020-21 Budget - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The 2020-21 Budget is committing record funding to rebuilding our economy and securing Australia’s future. Investing in apprenticeships, creating jobs and boosting the skills of Australians to help them get back into work is at the heart of the Government’s Economic Recovery Plan for Australia, along with guaranteeing the essential services Australians rely on. These services include supporting Australia’s education system through the continued provision of quality early childhood education, and funding certainty for schools and universities, while delivering more VET and higher education places, short courses and investing in research. The employment services system will continue to be reformed to be able to better meet the needs of Australians looking for work.

title: Tertiary Access Payment - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Tertiary Access Payment (TAP) is a non-indexed, means-tested payment to school-leavers from regional or remote areas who need to relocate for full-time, higher-level tertiary education (Certificate IV and above) at an education provider located at least 90 minutes by public transport from their family home.

title: 2024–25 Corporate Plan – Department of Education - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Corporate Plan is the Department of Education’s primary planning document. It sets out how the department will deliver on its purpose, to create a better future for all Australians through education. The plan details the department’s operating environment, enterprise-wide risks and our stakeholders. It also outlines how we will measure our performance, and the strategies we will employ to achieve our purpose for the 2024-28 forward years.

title: 2024–25 Education Portfolio Budget Statements and PAES - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The 2024-25 Department of Education Portfolio Budget Statements (PBS) provide information on the proposed allocation of funds to achieve government outcomes. title: Information Publication Scheme Agency Plan - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The department is an agency subject to the Freedom of Information Act 1982 (FOI Act) and is required to comply with the Information Publication Scheme (IPS) requirements. This Information Publication Scheme Agency Plan (Agency Plan) describes how the department proposes to do this, as required by subsection 8(1) of the FOI Act.

title: Department of Education Reconciliation Action Plan - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Reconciliation Action Plan August 2023-25 promotes the department’s vision for a reconciled Australia where Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, cultures and heritages are valued and accepted as a foundation for unity, equality, and enduring positive change. We will implement our Innovate RAP over the next two years to deliver on our commitments. Education will play a key role as we establish a shared understanding and commitment to implementing the plan.

title: Reconciliation Commitment 2023–2024 - Department of Education, Australian Government
description: The Department of Education is committed to reconciliation and improving outcomes for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples. This document outlines the priority actions the department is focused on whilst the Reconciliation Action Plan (RAP) is being developed in partnership with Reconciliation Australia.

title: Australian Government Guidelines on Information and Advertising Campaigns by non-corporate Commonwealth entities | Department of Finance
description: The Australian Government Guidelines on Information and Advertising Campaigns by non-corporate Commonwealth entities (Guidelines) have been updated and take effect from December 2022. They provide a framework for the conduct of all publicly-funded information and advertising campaigns by non-corporate Commonwealth entities.Australian Government Guidelines on Information and Advertising Campaigns [278 KB]Australian Government Guidelines on Information and Advertising Campaigns [65 KB]Finance is responsible for supporting the administration of the Guidelines. Entities should engage the Communications Branch of Finance early in the development of campaigns to ensure that relevant requirements are met.Non-corporate Commonwealth entities under the Public Governance, Performance and Accountability Act 2013 (PGPA Act) must comply with the Australian Government Guidelines on Information and Advertising Campaigns by non-corporate Commonwealth entities (Guidelines).
